Looking at this mutation, the change is from `if (!module.parent)` to `if (true)`. 

The original code `if (!module.parent)` means the block only executes when the module is run directly (not when it's required/imported). The mutated code `if (true)` means the block always executes, even when the module is imported.

The block contains `console.log("for testing purpose")` and other code including `let res = parse(url)` where `url = "https ://www.npmjs.com/package/electron-window-manager"` (note the space in the URL). It also calls `debugger`.

The key observable difference is that when the module is imported (required), the mutated version will execute `console.log("for testing purpose")`, while the original won't.

I can detect this by spying on `console.log` before importing the module and checking if it was called.

Wait, but the module is already loaded when the test file imports it. I need to think about this differently.

Actually, since Jest caches modules, I need to use `jest.resetModules()` and then dynamically require the module to observe the side effect. I can spy on `console.log` before the require happens.

```typescript
import { jest } from '@jest/globals';

describe('crawler-url-parser module loading behavior', () => {
  it('should not execute the testing block when required as a module', () => {
    // Spy on console.log before requiring the module
    const consoleSpy = jest.spyOn(console, 'log').mockImplementation(() => {});

    // Clear module cache to force re-execution of module-level code
    jest.resetModules();

    // Require the module - in original code, the if(!module.parent) block should NOT run
    // In mutated code (if(true)), the block WILL run and call console.log
    require('../../../../../../../../../../../subject_repositories/crawler-url-parser/crawler-url-parser.js');

    // Check if console.log was called with "for testing purpose"
    const wasCalledWithTestingPurpose = consoleSpy.mock.calls.some(
      call => call[0] === "for testing purpose"
    );

    // Restore the spy
    consoleSpy.mockRestore();

    // In original: module.parent is set (we're requiring it), so !module.parent is false
    // The block should NOT execute, so console.log should NOT have been called
    expect(wasCalledWithTestingPurpose).toBe(false);
  });
});
```

Looking at the mutation again: `if (!module.parent)` → `if (true)`.

When the module is required (imported), `module.parent` is set, so `!module.parent` is `false` and the block doesn't run. With `if (true)`, the block always runs.

The block calls `console.log("for testing purpose")`. I can detect this by spying on `console.log` before requiring the module.

